               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BODKIN</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430403-name-1219" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1219" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1219" type="surname" value="DUTTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1219" type="given" value="EMMA"></interp>EMMA DUTTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am housekeeper at Messrs. Golsing and Sharp, bankers, Fleet-street. The prisoner was in the habit of bringing bread from Mr. Inglis's to the house—I generally paid him weekly—this is the book in which it was entered when brought—here is 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 11<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and the prisoner's receipt in the book for these sums.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430403-name-1220" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1220" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1220" type="surname" value="INGLIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-1220" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS INGLIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am baker, and live in New-street, Covent-garden; the prisoner has been eleven years in my employ. It was his duty to take out bread, receive money, and to enter the sums he received in this cash-book every evening, and deliver it up to me—here is his cash-book—there is no entry of these sums as received from Gosling and Sharp—he has not ac<lb></lb>counted to me for either of these sums.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Your's is the the Digestive Bread Depot? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—all my servants have not robbed me—the prisoner was first deficient in his accounts in 1841—I never kept account of deficiencies</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184304030165"></xptr>
               <p>with the prisoner and charged him interest—in 1841 the amount of 50<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. odd was found out against him—I told him I must apply to a Magistrate—he said, if I kept him on, he would pay 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a week, and become a new man—his wife was not in my employ then—she had been—he continued making pay<lb></lb>ments of 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. and 9<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a week down to the time he was taken—it amounted to upwards of 50<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—he had got a very excellent business in a china-shop—he solicited all my customers, and got their orders—he told me himself it was a thriving concern—Hannah Wissencroft lived in my service about twelve months—she had not a little baby with her when she went away—I had no particular quarrel with the prisoner—I was very angry with him when I found out that he was a thief, and it was his own proposition, to save him from dis<lb></lb>grace, if I would keep him—since that offence he became a tee-totaler and a most pious man—he was steady and industrious—I had persons of the name of Newton and James in my service—they were deficient, and when I found them out I turned them away—I did not take 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. from the prisoner besides the 50<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I am quite sure of that, if he made a wrong entry, he rectified it.</p>
               <p>
